## Known Findings (do not duplicate)

- F-001: Oracle decimal scaling is ignored, so non-18-decimal feeds misprice collateral by orders of magnitude (High, high)
- F-002: Rewards claimed while no borrow shares exist become permanently stranded in the pair (Medium, high)
- F-003: Unchecked Convex staking results can leave credited collateral unstaked and later lock withdrawals/liquidations (Medium, medium)
- F-004: Convex pool migration mishandles the sentinel `pid == 0` and can orphan all collateral (High, high)
- F-005: Unconditional reward claiming can globally freeze borrowing, repayments, withdrawals, and liquidations (High, medium)
- F-007: Zero oracle prices cause division-by-zero reverts across critical pair flows (High, medium)
- F-009: Share-refactor floor rounding can leak small amounts of debt and leave unowned borrow shares (Low, medium)
- F-010: Excess redemption write-offs are silently discarded, leaving phantom collateral in borrower accounting (High, high)
- F-012: Allowing `minimumLeftoverDebt = 0` can preserve stale global borrow shares after full redemption (Low, medium)
- F-013: Reward-manager invalidation can disable the internal write-off token and break redemption accounting (Medium, high)
- F-016: Constructor bypasses the max-LTV safety cap enforced by the runtime setter (High, high)
- F-019: Any registered reward token that misbehaves can freeze borrower-facing pair operations (Medium, high)
- F-021: Interest overflow silently forgives accrued debt and permanently skips the elapsed interval (High, high)
- F-022: Invalidating a reward token strands already accrued user rewards and pair-held balances (Medium, high)
- F-023: Constructor bypasses the liquidation-fee and protocol-redemption-fee caps enforced by runtime setters (High, high)
- F-025: Mint fee is uncapped, so governance can make new borrows immediately confiscatory (Medium, high)
- F-026: Oracle and rate-calculator setters accept invalid addresses and can globally brick the pair (Medium, high)
- F-029: Convex pool configuration never validates that a `pid` matches the pair collateral (Medium, high)
- F-030: Uncapped `minimumBorrowAmount` can make partial repayments and deleveraging impossible for existing borrowers (Medium, high)
- F-031: Zero `epochLength` in the core contract permanently bricks pair fee withdrawals (Low, high)

